Subject: [PATCH] NCollection_BaseAllocator: per-thread CommonBaseAllocator (freed at thread exit)

The single process-wide CommonBaseAllocator singleton is copied into every
NCollection container ctor/dtor, so its atomic refcount is a true-sharing
hotspot: under multithreaded DataExchange (parallel STEP convert) every core
RMWs the same cache line, capping in-process scaling at ~3.5x on a 10-P-core
box regardless of jemalloc/mutex changes. A per-thread instance keeps refcount
traffic core-local (measured 3.5x -> ~8.5x, output bit-identical). The allocator
is stateless (a malloc wrapper) and handle refcounting keeps each thread's
instance alive across any cross-thread handoff, so this is semantics-preserving.

Held BY VALUE (not a thread_local raw pointer): a `new occ::handle<...>` per
thread would leak one Handle + allocator for every worker thread that ever
touches OCCT. A by-value thread_local Handle runs its destructor at thread exit,
dropping only that thread's ref — containers that copied the Handle keep the
allocator alive until their own refs drop, so freeing here is safe (and the main
thread's instance lives for the whole process as before).
--- a/src/FoundationClasses/TKernel/NCollection/NCollection_BaseAllocator.cxx
+++ b/src/FoundationClasses/TKernel/NCollection/NCollection_BaseAllocator.cxx
@@ CommonBaseAllocator
-  static occ::handle<NCollection_BaseAllocator>* THE_SINGLETON_ALLOC =
-    new occ::handle<NCollection_BaseAllocator>(new NCollection_BaseAllocator);
-  return *THE_SINGLETON_ALLOC;
+  static thread_local occ::handle<NCollection_BaseAllocator> THE_SINGLETON_ALLOC(
+    new NCollection_BaseAllocator);
+  return THE_SINGLETON_ALLOC;
